# Decision Templates Library

## Overview
This prompt instructs an AI development tool to build the Decision Templates Library for Archject, a focused approval and decision-tracking solution for design projects. The system will provide opinionated, reusable templates for common decision types (finishes, layouts, change requests) to accelerate decision creation, paired with a robust Decisions List / Content Browser, a multi-step Create/Edit Decision Page, and a Project Workspace Page. The deliverables enable canonical decision management, visual side-by-side option comparisons, automated reminders, and policy-driven approvals, all within Archject’s branding and design system.

## Components to Build
1) Decision Templates Library (opinionated templates)
- Purpose: Define reusable decision templates for common decision types (e.g., finishes, layouts, change requests) with predefined metadata, required fields, default approval rules, and option sets.
- Data model: Template with fields for name, type, description, required metadata, option schemas (images, specs, layouts), default approval rules, versioning, usage analytics.
- APIs: CRUD for templates (workspace admins and shared/public templates), apply-template to prepopulate decision flow, analytics hooks (usage counts, last-used, success rate).
- UX considerations: Template catalog with search, categories, preview of template structure, “Apply Template” action that preloads the Create Decision flow with template defaults, audit trail of template usage.

2) Decisions List / Content Browser
- Purpose: Canonical list of all decisions across a project with robust filtering, sortable views, and quick previews. Bulk actions include share links, export, and status changes.
- Data model: Decision objects linked to projects, with fields for metadata, status, assignees, due dates, options, version, and audit trail.
- Features:
  - Filters: by status, type, assignee, due date, priority, template used, creation date, tags, and custom facets.
  - Bulk actions: share link generation, export (CSV/JSON/PDF), bulk status updates, bulk assignee changes, bulk export of decision packs.
  - Quick preview: inline panel with summary cards, key options, and a one-click open to full editor.
  - Sorting and views: list, card, and table views; saved filters and recently viewed.
  - Permissions: workspace admins and project members with appropriate read/write controls.
- UX: Card layouts with status badges, option thumbnails, and flow indicators; large tap targets; keyboard accessible controls.

3) Create / Edit Decision Page (Multi-step Editor)
- Purpose: Create or edit a Decision Object via a guided, multi-step flow.
- Steps (modular, collapsible):
  1) Metadata: title, decision type (from templates or custom), project association, category, priority, due date, tags.
  2) Options Upload: upload and manage options (images, specifications, layouts, CAD exports); drag-and-drop uploader; validation for file types and max sizes; thumbnails; option-level metadata.
  3) Side-by-Side Comparison Setup: define groups/columns, align options, compare trade-offs with visual diff of materials, finishes, costs; allow users to mark favored options.
  4) Approval Rules: define approvers, approval workflow stages, required sign-offs, escalation policies, conditional rules.
  5) Assignee & Schedule: assign owner, set reminders (email, in-app, calendar), due date, and escalation notifications.
  6) Review & Publish: summary, validation, generate shareable link, archive/clone, or finalize decision with timestamped approval.
- Features:
  - Real-time collaboration-friendly editor with change tracking and comments per step.
  - Validation: required fields per decision type, file-size limits, and approval rule consistency.
  - Previews: render option thumbnails, summary view, and a printable/exportable decision pack.
  - Automation hooks: when published, trigger reminders and exportable decision logs.
- UX: Progressive disclosure, strong visual hierarchy, status indicators, and contextual help. Consistent with the design system (cards, typography, spacing, color use).

4) Project Workspace Page
- Purpose: Provide a project-level workspace that lists decisions, project files, team members, templates, and project overview (branding and settings).
- Features:
  - Branding: project-specific logos, color tokens, and header branding.
  - Tabs/Sections: Decisions, Files, Team, Templates, Overview/Settings.
  - Decision overview: quick stats (open decisions, overdue, average cycle time), search, and filters.
  - Files: integrated file manager or link to repository, with versioning and quick-glance metadata.
  - Team: members, roles, invite controls, and activity feed.
  - Templates: access to Decision Templates Library with publishable templates for project scope.
- UX: Cohesive, modular cards and panels; responsive layout; consistent navigation and micro-interactions.

